---
import PageLayout from "@layouts/PageLayout.astro";
import Container from "@components/Container.astro";
import Link from "@components/Link.astro";
import { SITE, SOCIALS } from "@consts";
---

<PageLayout title="About" description="About me">
  <Container>
    <div class="space-y-10">
      <div class="animate font-semibold text-brand-steel/85">
        About
      </div>
      <div class="animate space-y-6">
        <div class="space-y-4">
          <p class="font-semibold text-brand-steel/85">So What Is This?</p>
          <p>
            I'm Seej. Hardware engineering by education, systems engineer by training,
            AI enthusiast by interest. I tend to collect skills the way some people collect
            hobbies. Which is also to say I collect hobbies. Photography, watercolor, sketching,
            and whatever else catches my eye.
          </p>
          <p>
            Married, with a mini-Aussie named Momo who has strong opinions about everything.
            Big lover of space and space-adjacent things. This blog is where all of it lands.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="space-y-4">
          <p class="font-semibold text-brand-steel/85">Why The Hexagons?</p>
          <p>
            The hexagon is nature's favorite tile. Honeycombs, basalt columns, snowflakes, the eyes of a dragonfly, the cells of a turtle's shell. Wherever something needs to pack tightly, share edges efficiently, and hold together under stress, the hexagon shows up. It's the only regular polygon besides the triangle and square that tessellates the plane on its own, and of those three it's the most efficient: maximum area, minimum perimeter, every neighbor an equal partner.
          </p>
          <p>
            What the hexagon gets right is that structure isn't planned, it's accumulated. Each cell locks into the ones already there. The pattern isn't decided in advance and then filled in. It grows outward from wherever you started, and it holds because of how the edges connect, not because someone drew the whole thing first.
          </p>
          <p>
            That's how this works. A photography project teaches you about aesthetics in ways that show up everywhere. Working in the garden teaches you about solar panel technology in space. None of it is wasted. Each tile adds an edge that the next one can lock into. Over time the surface becomes load-bearing.
          </p>
          <p>
            No single tile tells the whole story. But look at enough of them together and the shape of a person starts to emerge. This site is that surface. Still being laid. ⬢
          </p>
          <p>
            Though if you stare at it long enough. Are you sure it's not a black cube?
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="space-y-2">
          <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-brand-steel/85">Get in touch</p>
          <ul class="flex flex-wrap gap-2">
            {SOCIALS.map(SOCIAL => (
              <li class="flex gap-x-2 text-nowrap">
                <Link href={SOCIAL.HREF} external aria-label={`${SITE.NAME} on ${SOCIAL.NAME}`}>
                  {SOCIAL.NAME}
                </Link>
                {"•"}
              </li>
            ))}
            <li class="line-clamp-1">
              <Link href={`mailto:${SITE.EMAIL}`} aria-label={`Email ${SITE.NAME}`}>
                {SITE.EMAIL}
              </Link>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </Container>
</PageLayout>
